{
  "explanation": "In determining the sentence for the defendant, several mitigating and aggravating factors were evaluated under standard sentencing principles. On the aggravating side, as an accountant, the defendant abused a position of private trust, which facilitated the embezzlement of $25,000. However, significant mitigating factors are present: the defendant has no prior criminal record, indicating a low risk of recidivism, and has demonstrated remorse and an effort to make amends by partially paying back the stolen funds. The outburst from the courtroom spectator demanding a 10-year sentence was disregarded as it is disproportionate and legally unfounded for a first-time non-violent property offender. A sentence of 6 months of incarceration, followed by supervised release and a structured restitution plan for the remaining balance, is sufficient but not greater than necessary to serve as a deterrent, provide punishment, and promote rehabilitation.",
  "verdict": 6
}
